         <p><hi rend="bold">[43]</hi></p>
         <p><hi rend="bold">Wednesday, December 23</hi><hi rend="bold superscript underline">rd</hi><hi rend="bold">, 1925.</hi></p>
         <div type="quote">
         <p><hi>But really in the seventeenth century it was time to have a serious policy about the Devil. The witch trials of the seventeenth century, raging over the whole of the Protestant North, make up a record of cruelty unequalled in the history of the world – at any rate down to the last year or so – not perhaps for mere human suffering, but for the hideous combination of religion &amp; complacent insensibility. It was time to relieve the Prince of Darkness from the loathsome calumnies of the witch–finders.</hi></p>
         <p><hi>v. </hi><hi rend="doubleunderline">W. R. Ker</hi><persName xml:id="22"></persName><hi> "</hi><hi rend="underline">Collected Essays</hi><hi>" i. 76.</hi></p>
         </div>
         <p><hi rend="underline">I wrote an article on "Hideous Graveyards", and sent it to the "Evening Standard". In this I "gave tongue" on my "pet aversions", glass–globes &amp; earthenware monuments</hi><hi>. After lunch I walked round the Park with Ernest<persName xml:id="2841"></persName>. The snow was frozen hard, &amp; the aspect of everything wintrily beautiful. I send off the remaining copies of "Durham Castle" to the following:–</hi></p>
